Introduction: In this report, Red Wine dataset will be explored. The chemical properties of the wine will be taken care of and their effect on the quality of the wine. We will see that which variable will effect most on the quality of the wine(RED). At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). 11 attributes of Wine were considered e-g sugar content, salt content, acidic content,density, pH etc . So lets get started.

So our Data has Around 1600 observations and 13 Columns. One being a Quality Variable and First One is used for the Id (which will be dropped soon) other 11 variables define the factors on which Quality is dependent.

Moreover, Quality is shown as integer column, and it will be converted into categorical one as this is ordinal discrete variable which shows that the quality falls in which group.

Suprisingly, our dataset has quality ranging from 3 to 8, nono assign the value below 3, that is bad or above 8, that is very good wine.

Univariate Analysis

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

  • Quality It is our main feature of Interest as all the remaining variables are used to define the quality of Wine as perceived by the Wine Experts.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

-Alcholhol -citric Acid -Volatile Acidity -Suagr and alcohol ratio -Salt content(Chlorides) -Sulphates

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes. first of all Quality variable is converted into grouped bins, suagr and alcohol ratio was created by using residual sugar content variable and alcohol variable. Finally density and volatile acidity ratio was created fom the density variable and volatile acidity variable.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Removed Top 1% of dAta to correct the long tailed data. Converted density and sulpher dioxides variable on log scale for better visualization. Number of Bins were adjusted as well. Quality variable was transformed from integer to categorical variable, because it describes the levels rather than just numerical values

In residual sugar, top 5% are removed to avoid overplotting and outliers.

Ph is almost inversely related.As I have chemistry background, i thought it was obvious that Bad Quality wines have higher pH that is they Are more basic in nature rather acidic.

It is a compact display of a continous distribution. As expected, higher volatility leads to the bad quality of the wine, as it leaves the bad odour and taste after sometime.As volatile acidity incrreases, the quality of the Wine decreases.

One more correlation is seen between the ratio i created that is sugar alcohol ratio and the density. so lets plot them

Great, This shows that they are directly realted.Beacuse of the fact that when sugar content is increased, so does the alcohol content, which results in the increase in density.

Interestingly, citric Acid and Volatility are inversely related.

And more interestingly, fixed acidity and citric acid are directly related.

pH and citric acid are also inversely related to each other.

Here it is evedient that alcohol and density is inveresely related. as the chemical properties of the alcohol are suggestive of this behaviour that the density decreases as the alcohol content increases in the wine.

Reflection

It was an interesting dataset regarding Chemical properties of the Red Wine and Deciding wheather they are of good quality or Bad quality wine. The difficulty which i faced in exploring the data is finding relations of the variables with the qualtity directly. But once i categorize them, things become simpler comparatively.

We can Infer from above report that Alcohol, Sulphates, volatile acidity , citric Acid has significant effect on the quality of the wine. More the content of the Above chemicals , better is the quality of the Wine. Whereas, as expected, volatility is inversely related to the quality of the Wine. as higher volatile wine will lead to the foul smell after some time. So Better Quality wines have low Volatility.

This data would be better in deciding the relation of different chemical properties if there would be more data on the extremes. This Data has lack the points of extremes , which leads to non-decisive nature of Data.

Surprisingly, as we explored the Data we can conclude that sugar and chlorides dont have significant effect on the quality of the wine, But i think that it must have some effect on deciding the quality of the Wine. May be Due to shortage of Data, It is not evident Apparentely.
